post_cb({"29936940": {"ViewCount": "136", "Body": "<p>Afaik, every pair of <code>{ }</code> in the code creates a new scope. Even if it's used just for the sake of it without any <code>if</code>, <code>for</code>, function or other statement that demands it:</p>\n<pre><code>void myFun(void)\n{\n    int a;\n    {\n        int local;\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>I started wondering - when the <code>if</code> statement is written without using the braces (with 1-line body) does it still create a new scope?</p>\n<pre><code>voidmyFun(int a)\n{\n    int b;\n    if (a == 1)\n        int tmp;   // is this one local to if?\n    else\n        int tmp2;   // or this one?\n    b = 2;   // could I use tmp here?\n}\n</code></pre>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "29937137", "Title": "if statement without the inner scope?", "CreationDate": "2015-04-29T07:24:08.220", "Id": "29936940", "CommentCount": "3", "LastEditDate": "2015-04-29T07:46:37.327", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "2422776", "LastActivityDate": "2015-04-29T13:39:21.820", "Score": "4", "OwnerUserId": "1030598", "Tags": "<c++><variables><if-statement><scope>", "AnswerCount": "4"}, "29937011": {"Id": "29937011", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Yes! <code>tmp</code> are local to <code>if</code> and <code>tmp2</code> is local to <code>else</code>. If you try using <code>tmp</code> or <code>temp2</code> outside, you should get variable not defined error. It is because,</p>\n<pre><code>if(&lt;condition&gt;) &lt;my-statment&gt; \nif(&lt;condition&gt;) \n{ \n  &lt;my-statment&gt; \n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>For compiler, both of them are equal.</p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "3906965", "LastActivityDate": "2015-04-29T07:29:01.387", "Score": "2", "CreationDate": "2015-04-29T07:27:19.907", "ParentId": "29936940", "CommentCount": "1", "LastEditDate": "2015-04-29T07:29:01.387", "OwnerUserId": "3906965"}, "29937137": {"Id": "29937137", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>N4140 [stmt.select]/1 reads:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_29936940_29937137_0\">The substatement in a <em>selection-statement</em> (each substatement, in the <code>else</code> form of the <code>if</code> statement) implicitly defines a block scope</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>So, the code</p>\n<pre><code>if (a == 1)\n    int tmp;   // is this one local to if?\nelse\n    int tmp2;   // or this one?\n</code></pre>\n<p>is equivalent to</p>\n<pre><code>if (a == 1)\n{\n    int tmp;   // yes, this one is local to if\n}\nelse\n{\n    int tmp2;   // and this one as well\n}\n</code></pre>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "3959454", "LastActivityDate": "2015-04-29T09:36:19.553", "Score": "4", "CreationDate": "2015-04-29T07:32:36.760", "ParentId": "29936940", "CommentCount": "3", "LastEditDate": "2015-04-29T09:36:19.553", "OwnerUserId": "3959454"}, "29936985": {"Id": "29936985", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Yes, even if the if and for do not have <code>{}</code>, the variables declared in it are local to it.</p>\n<p>So, if you try something like</p>\n<pre><code>if ( something )\n    int a = 3;\nstd::cout &lt;&lt; a;  // there is no other identifier called a in your program\n</code></pre>\n<p>it will not compile, because it is the same as</p>\n<pre><code>if ( something )\n{\n    int a = 3;\n}\nstd::cout &lt;&lt; a;\n</code></pre>\n<p>and you will get a variable not declared in this scope error.</p>\n<p>So,</p>\n<pre><code>voidmyFun(int a)\n{\n    int b;\n    if (a == 1)\n        int tmp;   // is this one local to if?   Ans:-  Yes\n    else\n        int tmp2;   // or this one?          Ans:- It is local to else block\n    b = 2;   // could I use tmp here?      Ans:-  No\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>So, the variable inside the <code>else</code> ( <code>tmp2</code> ) is local to <code>else</code> and not to <code>if</code>.</p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "4516316", "LastActivityDate": "2015-04-29T07:31:19.887", "Score": "2", "CreationDate": "2015-04-29T07:26:09.743", "ParentId": "29936940", "CommentCount": "0", "LastEditDate": "2015-04-29T07:31:19.887", "OwnerUserId": "4516316"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_29936940_29937137_0": {"length": 11, "quality": 0.9166666666666666, "section_id": 3882}}, "n3337": {"so_29936940_29937137_0": {"length": 11, "quality": 0.9166666666666666, "section_id": 3742}}, "n4659": {"so_29936940_29937137_0": {"length": 11, "quality": 0.9166666666666666, "section_id": 4771}}}, "29937005": {"Id": "29937005", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>In short - yes. It's a single line scope.</p>\n<p>In other words, writing:</p>\n<pre><code>if (someCondition) \n    int i = 7;\n</code></pre>\n<p>Is identical, scope-wise, to writing:</p>\n<pre><code>if (someCondition) \n{\n    int i = 7;\n}\n</code></pre>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2015-04-29T07:26:54.767", "Score": "2", "CreationDate": "2015-04-29T07:26:54.767", "ParentId": "29936940", "CommentCount": "0", "OwnerUserId": "2422776"}});